     bits 1–0 = 11       = top 2 effective bits of byte[1]
   This constrains 9 of the 56 effective DES key bits, leaving 47 unknown.


-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
2. DES CIPHER BACKGROUND
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------

DES (Data Encryption Standard) is a 64-bit block cipher standardized by
NIST in 1977.  Each 8-byte block is encrypted independently with the same
key in ECB (Electronic Code Book) mode.

The 64-bit key has 56 effective bits (every 8th bit is an odd-parity check
bit that carries no key information).  The cipher's internal pipeline is:

  Plaintext (64 bits)
    --> IP (Initial Permutation)
    --> 16 Feistel rounds, each using a 48-bit round subkey
    --> FP (Final Permutation = IP^-1)
  Ciphertext (64 bits)

Each Feistel round:
  1. Expand the 32-bit right half R to 48 bits (E expansion)
  2. XOR with the 48-bit round subkey (from the key schedule)
  3. Feed through eight S-boxes (6 bits in, 4 bits out each)
  4. Permute the 32-bit S-box output (P permutation)
  5. XOR the result into the left half L
  6. Swap L and R

Key schedule: PC1 splits the 56 key bits into two 28-bit halves C and D.
Each round, C and D are left-rotated by 1 or 2 bits; PC2 then selects 48
bits from {C, D} to form the round subkey.  The total rotation across all
16 rounds is 28 bits (a full circle), so C(16) = C(0).  This property is
exploited for on-the-fly key scheduling during decryption (see section 3).

SP-table optimization: the eight S-boxes plus the P permutation are
combined into eight 64-entry lookup tables (SP1–SP8), each mapping 6 bits
to 32 bits.  This eliminates the S-box and P-permutation loops and is the
standard technique in fast software DES implementations (Eric Young's
libdes, SSL, etc.).

Pre-rotated IP/FP: this implementation uses a further optimization where
the IP includes a ROL-1 of each half, and the FP includes the matching
ROR-1.  This lets the Feistel function align the 6-bit SP-box groups with
a simple ROR-4, avoiding per-round bit extraction.  The SP entries are
pre-rotated to match.

DES is reciprocal under key reversal: decrypting is identical to
encrypting except that the 16 subkeys are applied in reverse order.


-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
3. BREAKING THE CIPHER — GPU BRUTE FORCE
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------

Key space reduction:
  Total DES effective key bits:    56
  Known from Stage 8:               9  (7 of byte[0], 2 of byte[1])
  Remaining unknown bits:          47
  Keys to search:                 2^47 ≈ 140.7 trillion

Filtering strategy (no known plaintext crib needed):
  English prose encrypted with DES will have essentially all printable
  ASCII bytes (0x20–0x7E, 0x0A, 0x0D).  A random 8-byte block has only
  a ~0.02% chance of being all-printable.

  Filter 1: decrypt block 0; if not all-ASCII, discard (eliminates 99.98%)
  Filter 2: decrypt blocks 1–9; require ≥50% all-ASCII (eliminates false
            positives from Filter 1, at the cost of ~10× more work per
            surviving candidate — but surviving candidates are extremely rare)

GPU implementation (crack_des_cuda.cu):
  Platform:  NVIDIA RTX 3090 (Ampere SM 8.6, 82 SMs, 10496 CUDA cores)
  Throughput: ~3.77 billion keys/second
  Run time:  7112 seconds (~2 hours) to find the key

  Key optimizations:
  * On-the-fly key schedule: instead of pre-storing all 32 subkey words
    (128 bytes/thread), subkeys are computed from C, D inside the Feistel
    loop.  For decryption, start at C(16) = C(0) and walk backwards,
    right-rotating by KEY_SHIFTS[round] after each use.  This saves 128
    bytes of register/local memory per thread, dramatically improving SM
    occupancy.
  * SP tables in shared memory: the 512-entry SP table (2 KiB) is copied
    from global to per-block shared memory at kernel launch.  Constant
    memory serialises divergent warp accesses; shared memory serves them
    in parallel (modulo bank conflicts).
  * No plaintext storage: each block's ASCII status is checked inline and
    the plaintext bytes are never stored.
  * #pragma unroll: the 16-round loop is fully unrolled by the compiler.

  Key index encoding: the 47-bit key_idx encodes the 47 unknown bits:
    bits [46:42] → byte[1] effective bits [4:0]  (top 2 bits fixed = 11)
    bits [41:35] → byte[2] effective bits [6:0]
    bits [34:28] → byte[3] effective bits [6:0]
    bits [27:21] → byte[4] effective bits [6:0]
    bits [20:14] → byte[5] effective bits [6:0]
    bits [13:7]  → byte[6] effective bits [6:0]
    bits [6:0]   → byte[7] effective bits [6:0]

  The search found the key at index ≈ 19% of the way through the space,
  after testing ≈ 26.7 trillion candidate keys.

Key found:  D3CD1694CBA126FE

Verification:  DES_decrypt(block_0_of_text.d, key) = "O! curse" ✓


-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
4. CIPHERTEXT CORRUPTION
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------

The ciphertext was transcribed from the printed book via scan + OCR + hand-
correction.  Two of the 139 blocks were corrupted in this process.

des_diag.c (diagnostic) decrypts all blocks with the correct key and checks
which ones produce non-ASCII output.  It found exactly two bad blocks:

  Block 130 (offset 0x410, bytes 1040–1047):
    Corrupted CT: d2 ab ed 2f ca 2d e1 2b
    Raw decryption: 82 b7 35 fe fa 93 89 13  (not ASCII)
    Context: block 129 = "y factor", block 131 = "public m"
    Expected plaintext: "ing the "  (fitting "by factor[ing the ]public m")

    Fix: des_fix_ciphertext.c re-encrypts "ing the " with the correct key
    to compute the correct ciphertext bytes (22 72 7b ad b5 9e 0d c2) and
    patches them into the binary file at offset 0x410.

  Block 138 (offset 0x450, bytes 1104–1111):
    Corrupted CT: 0e b6 a9 76 ea d7 3a fd
    Raw decryption: 96 1e b0 cc 7b 34 2c 00  (not ASCII)
    This is the last block.  It is padding (or trailing garbage from the
    transcription error).  The preceding block 137 decrypts to " luck!\n\n",
    which is the natural end of the message.

    Fix: des_fix_ciphertext.c writes a truncated version (1104 bytes, 138
    blocks) that omits this block entirely.  The full 1112-byte version with
    only block 130 patched is also written.

Output files:
  text_fixed.d        — 1112 bytes, block 130 patched, block 138 still corrupt
  text_fixed_trunc.d  — 1104 bytes, block 130 patched, corrupt last block removed


