6. DECRYPTED PLAINTEXT
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------

O! cursed, cursed slave.  Whip me, ye devils,
From the possession of this heavenly sight!
Blow me about in winds! roast me in sulphur!
Wash me in steep-down gulfs of liquid fire!
O Desdemona! Desdemona! dead!

Only one more phase to go.  Your token for this one is "Armstrong".

The final hurdle contains two ciphertexts.  The longer one is
encrypted with triple-DES in electronic code book mode.  It uses a
128-bit EDE key.

The RSA public key cryptosystem has been used to encipher the
triple-DES key; this forms the shorter ciphertext.  The public
exponent is 3735928559 in decimal and the public modulus is the
following 155-digit decimal integer:

10742 78829 12665 65907 17841 12799 42116 61266 39217 94753 29458
88778 17210 35546 41509 80121 87903 38329 26235 28109 07506 72083
50494 19964 33143 42555 83344 01855 80898 94268 92463.

Your task is to decipher the longer message and so discover the final
code word.  How you do this is up to you, but it will almost certainly
be much, much easier to break the RSA ciphertext by factoring the
public modulus than by any other approach.

Good luck!

Source: Shakespeare, Othello, Act V, scene ii (Othello's dying speech).
The fragment begins at "O! cursed, cursed slave."

Note: The last few bytes of the plaintext contain garbage characters
("°Ì{4, .").  This is an artefact of the corrupted transcription of
block 138 and can be ignored.


-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
7. STAGE 10 CONTEXT
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------

The plaintext reveals the full setup for Stage 10:

  * The Stage 10 message is encrypted with triple-DES (3DES) in ECB mode,
    using a 128-bit EDE key (two 64-bit DES keys: K1, K2).
    EDE means: encrypt with K1, decrypt with K2, encrypt with K1 again.

  * The 3DES key itself is RSA-encrypted, forming a shorter ciphertext.

  * RSA public exponent:  3735928559  (= 0xDEADBEEF)
  * RSA public modulus:   155-digit integer shown in the plaintext above.

  * The recommended attack is to factor the modulus.  At publication time
    (1999), this was a serious challenge; modern factoring algorithms
    (GNFS) can handle ~155-digit numbers on a standard PC.


-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
8. FILES
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------

  crack_des_cuda.cu       -- GPU brute-force DES cracker (CUDA, RTX 3090)
                             Implements DES decryption with SP-table
                             optimization and on-the-fly key schedule.
                             Self-tests against NIST vectors.  Decrypts
                             full ciphertext once a candidate key is found.

  des_diag.c              -- Diagnostic: compare textbook DES with SP-table
                             DES round-by-round to verify correctness.
                             Used during development to identify bugs in the
                             IP/FP implementation and PC2 packing.

  des_fix_ciphertext.c    -- Identifies corrupted ciphertext blocks, computes
                             correct replacements by re-encrypting known
                             plaintext, patches the binary file, and writes
                             corrected output (text_fixed.d, text_fixed_trunc.d).

  text.d                  -- Original ciphertext (1112 bytes, 2 bad blocks)
  text_fixed.d            -- Block 130 patched (1112 bytes)
  text_fixed_trunc.d      -- Block 130 patched, block 138 removed (1104 bytes)
  text_fixed.uue          -- UU-encoded version of text_fixed.d
  text_fixed_trunc.uue    -- UU-encoded version of text_fixed_trunc.d
  plaintext.txt           -- Final decrypted output (written by crack_des_cuda)
  analyze_result.txt      -- Full block-by-block diagnostic dump (from des_diag.c)
  fix_result.txt          -- Output of des_fix_ciphertext.c
  DEBUGGER.BIN            -- 8-byte Stage 8 hint: DES_decrypt("DEBUGGER", key9)
  README                  -- This file
